06920nam a22011895i 9783839415375DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20142010gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)892891205  a97838394153757 a10.1515/transcript.97838394153752doi  a(DE-B1597)395890  a(OCoLC)885021204  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aART0090002bisacsh0481ua304.82qDE-101222/ger00aImages of Illegalized Immigration :bTowards a Critical Iconology of Politics /ced. by Francesca Falk, Christine Bischoff, Sylvia Kafehsy.  a1. Aufl. 1aBielefeld : btranscript Verlag, c[2014] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (178 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aImage ;v900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tMigration, Law, and the Image: Beyond the Veil of Ignorance -- tMilieus of Illegality -- tThe Making of “Illegality”: Strategies of Illegalizing Social Outsiders -- tCopying Camouflage -- tImages of Victims in Trafficking in Women -- tInvasion, Infection, Invisibility: An Iconology of Illegalized Immigration -- tVoice-Over Image -- tMasking, Blurring, Replacing: Can the Undocumented Migrant Have a Face in Film? -- tBorder: The Videographic Traces by Laura Waddington as a Cinematographic Memorial -- tPolitics, Representation, Visibility: Bruno Serralongue at the Cité Nationale de l’Histoire de l’Immigration -- tThe Image versus the Map: the Ceuta Border -- tWho is a Refugee—Strategies of Visibilization in the Neighbourhood of a Refugee Reception Camp and a Detention Centre -- tEditors and Authors -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIllegalized immigration is a highly iconic topic. The public perception of the current regime for mobility is profoundly shaped by visual and verbal images. As the issue of illegalized immigration is gaining increasing political momentum, the authors feel it is a well-warranted undertaking to analyze the role of images in the creation of illegalization. Their aim is to trace the visual processes that produce these very categories.The authors aim to map out an iconography of illegalized immigration in relation to political, ethical, and aesthetic discourses. They discuss the need to project new images as well as the dangers of giving persons without legal papers an individual face. Illegalization is produced by law, but naturalized through the everyday use of images. The production of law, on the other hand, is also driven by both mental and materialized images. A critical iconology may help us to see these mechanisms.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aCultural Studies. 4aFine Arts. 4aIconology. 4aIllegalization. 4aImage. 4aImmigration. 4aMigration. 4aPolitics. 4aVisual Studies. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies.  aFine Arts.  aIconology.  aIllegalization.  aImage.  aImmigration.  aMigration.  aPolitics.  aVisual Studies.1 aAndreas, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Olaf, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBischoff, Christine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBischoff, Christine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDousson, Lambert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Francesca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalk, Francesca, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFriedrichs, Jan-Henrik, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKafehsy, Sylvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKafehsy, Sylvia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/